==Seek time needs clarification==

Typical current mass-market drives are quoted as having ''seek'' times of around 9ms. this is just the time to move the head to the correct radial position, but it doesn't include rotation of the disk to the right sector. to get the real seek time, you need to add rotational latency, which is 4.1ms for a 7200 RPM drive (60 seconds per minute divided by 7200 RPM divided by 2 (for average)) and you have an average access time of about 13.5ms. A seriously high-perforance drive has a seek time of under 4ms and latency of 2ms - i.e., 6ms average access. But these drives sacrifice capacity to achieve their very high performance, require a SCSI interface, and are fairly expensive. [[User:Tannin|Tannin]]

